n understanding of the Gayatri mantra, with the Sun as the devata. This foll=\r\nows the famous verse from the Agastya Smriti -- =93yo devaH savitA  .asmAka=\r\nm dhiyo dharmAdigocarAH. prerayet tasya yad bhargaH tad vareNyam upAsmahe=\r\n=94. \n\n        We meditate upon (dhiimahi) the splendor / tejas (bhargaH) o=\r\nf the deva (devasya) that is the Sun (savituH). This tejas is the light of =\r\nthe sun, which is experienced by all living beings, and is thus easy to med=\r\nitate upon.\n\n        Whatever is experienced is easy to meditate upon, and =\r\nthat which is not experienced can be difficult to meditate upon. Everyone c=\r\nan meditate upon the light of the Sun. This is why this meaning for the Gay=\r\natri mantra is always taken first. \n\n        vareNyam =3D whatever we can a=\r\nsk / desire. Through all karmas and upaasanaas, whatever fruits we may ask =\r\nfor is vareNyam. =93Savitaa&quot; is the fruit of all karmas ... this is taught =\r\nin the Chandogya Upanishad. [ A long explanation follows, which is omitted =\r\nhere ].  We meditate upon the splendor of the sun, which is vareNyam.\n\n    =\r\n    We meditate upon that Savitaa (yaH) who impels (prachodayaat) our (naH)=\r\n thoughts (dhiyaH). He blesses us with subtle eyesight. Without his light, =\r\nwe would not be able to distinguish different objects. This is explained in=\r\n the Aitaterya Upanishad =93The sun, having become eyesight, entered the ey=\r\nes=94. He thus blesses all living beings. \n\n        ----\n\n        Sent from=\r\n Windows Mail\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  \r\n--Boundary_(ID_gIzvbAcxN9tfqGJJP5opRA)\r\nContent-type: text/html; charset=Windows-1252\r\nContent-transfer-encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.=\r\nw3c.org/TR/1999/REC-html401-19991224/loose.dtd&quot;&gt;\n&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt;\n&lt;META http-eq=\r\nuiv=3DContent-Type content=3D&quot;text/html; charset=3Dwindows-12